snippet.textDisplay:
@Rinkoo Kukreja only internet rumors think it's an engineered virus vs process of virus mutation like other viruses.

A PhD biologist channel also explained that viruses, like other life (a virus doesn't have a cell so most experts don't define it as alive, it's kinda borderline living), seek to *replicate themselves into the future* . Basic Darwin's evolution and experience hints that virus mutations that become more successful in spreading around and into the future, they typically become *less deadly* over time, because the more deadly forms kill the host and the virus dies off. That's why the *common cold virus* (which can be a rhinovirus or maybe other form of coronavirus) is *common* .. it's so mild that we just accept it and spread it without expending huge resources to stomp it out.

snippet.textDisplay:
I had instructors and professors like this.   But even the best professors ran into similar problems that required their teaching style to be roughed up: Depending on the level of class (if students were majoring or not in the subject) students' eyes would often glaze over, and during quizzes or questions the teacher would need to slow down, or repeat the lecture in a very jerky fashion, often running out of time and rushing through content in order to at least make it the test, paper, or final.  
Higher level courses, they move through subjects roughly as quick as this guy did, sometimes even quicker; thus making time for practical experiments, demonstrations, reviews, and moving on to more content.  


And some classes are literally bullshit classes; either the subject is too vague or the teacher doesn't like or understand the subject matter.... filler courses to make the school more money honey.... they and you know what classes I'm talking about.
  Fortunately for myself, I had very few those teachers or conditions in which the class was not so great.  The worst was taking tests on content we hadn't gone over yet, and nothing we did go over and told to study and read was on the test.  And the teacher on every test realizing this as students would ask him, and he'd either have to hint a few answers or give a few just so we could pass the class; particularly if you never took any prior weather/meteorology classes.   Was glad I had, it helped a little, but those tests were still pretty stormy. 



I thought this guy was excellent too.
But wait for the test at the end of the lesson. ;)~

If you happen to have the virus, you should be in the group that will get over it. You may not feel well, but keep hydrated and monitor your breathing and your pulse ox when you get it. The group's that haven't done well seem to be the elderly and those with other underlying conditions.  I wish you well!

snippet.textDisplay: @RosheEntertains Regardless of getting the test, you should be evaluated by your physician if you have fever, body aches, confusion, lightheartedness and chest pain. Call ahead in case they want to separate you from other patients.  Once you see your physician,  you can discuss about what your doctor thinks, then bring up whether they would test you for regular flu, or possibly Covid 19. Good luck, don't wait. Hope you get better.

snippet.textDisplay: Very amazing work. Thank you so much for putting all of the components in an easy to understand format. Have a question about RSV. I have pneumonia now, waiting for results (maybe 4 days?), my daughter and I had RSV 3 years ago. She had symptoms early (cough, fever, fatigue), but being 4, she did not meet test criteria. After almost 2 weeks of treating her at home, she started feeling better. Then I had a fever, chills, fatigue, productive cough. After 3 days, I went to my doctor, negative flu, negative strep, had pneumonia. Told them I definitely needed a covid test. It was very hard to get tested. Now I am waiting for results and don't know what the next step is. Any ideas? Quarantine, I have been.
